  "updated_summary": "The narrative begins with a sepia-toned collage of historical figures including Joseph Stalin, John F. Kennedy, Joan of Arc, Hannibal, Margaret Thatcher, Chairman Mao, Martin Luther King Jr., Caesar Augustus, and Adolf Hitler, set against a dramatic orchestral score, before a 'RISE OF NAPOLEON' title card appears. Sweeping aerial views of a rugged coastline and a Mediterranean coastal city transition to a stylized map highlighting Corsica, with a narrator explaining Napoleon Bonaparte's birth there on August 15, 1769, and France's recent acquisition of the island from the Republic of Genoa. Professor David Andress, positioned against a brick wall, explains that prior to the French Revolution, Napoleon, from the minor gentry of a recently incorporated region, was 'essentially condemned to mediocrity' with a 'moderately influential' family. Dr. Michael Rowe, also against a brick wall, adds that Napoleon had many siblings, experienced 'a lot of outdoor activities,' 'not a lot of luxury,' and had a down-to-earth mother named Leticia, whose portrait in elaborate 18th-century attire concludes the segment. The video then shifts focus to Napoleon's father, Carlo, described by Dr. Rowe as 'useless' with family finances and prone to gambling, leaving his family impoverished. A female voice introduces Carlo Bonaparte and his wife Letitia, pregnant with Napoleon, who had initially resisted the French takeover alongside Corsican nationalist leader Pasquale Paoli. However, after the resistance failed, Carlo Bonaparte, 'reading the writing on the wall,' decided to 'change tack,' leading Dr. Rowe to explain how the French asserted control, causing Carlo and the family to switch from Corsican independence 'pro-Paoli freedom fighters' to 'collaborators.' Dr. Rowe's voice then details how the French monarchy integrated Corsica by having prominent families send their sons into service, including Napoleon into the army, a move that 'troubles Napoleon as he grows up.' Professor David Andress elaborates that Napoleon became an artillery officer, a position considered 'lower class' by the aristocracy due to its requirement of specialized knowledge. In the hierarchical France of the 1780s, Napoleon was 'stewing his own ambitions' but wouldn't be allowed to 'ascend to greatness,' as Dr. Rowe concludes that Napoleon was 'not satisfied with his position.'"
